<section class="bg-eai-parchment text-eai-blueprint">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-20 md:py-24">
    <p class="font-mono text-[11px] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-eai-gold mb-5">
      Why this exists
    </p>
    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none font-serif text-eai-navy/90 leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        America's school trust lands have been running as a multi-generational
        fiduciary experiment for 240 years. No other intergenerational trust in
        American civic life has a record this long, this large, or this
        consequential. The trust covers tens of millions of acres across twenty
        states. Its corpus exceeds a hundred billion dollars. Its beneficiaries
        are public schoolchildren in every generation, including the ones not
        yet born. And the record — which the Library at schooltrusts.net
        preserves in detail — shows exactly how such trusts drift, fail,
        recover, and bind across centuries.
      </p>
      <p>
        The same architectural weaknesses recur in every case where the compact
        has loosened: fiduciary duty understated, restoration mechanisms
        missing, specialized legal defense absent, trustee education informal,
        and — most consequentially — no standing civic community holding the
        trust to its purpose across generations. The Eighth Anchor Institute
        studies these recurring failure modes in the school-trust record and
        applies the lessons to the new intergenerational trusts being designed
        right now: forever-funds for AI governance, multi-generational climate
        adaptation finance, treaty-based obligations to indigenous nations,
        religious and educational endowments, sovereign wealth funds intended
        to outlive their founding generations. The school trust is the worked
        example. The next century's trusts are the application.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
